data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for your test:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);  // or CollectionAssert.That is not built-in,
    // so use:
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    // For a predicate check, MSTest doesn't have a direct equivalent,
    // but you can use:
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // this one is acceptable
    // OR loop with individual asserts

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key MSTest replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, list.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, list.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` |

**Additional `CollectionAssert` methods:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` — item exists
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` — no duplicates
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)` — no nulls
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order & elements
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order

The benefit: when tests fail, these give specific messages (e.g., "Expected: 3, Actual: 2") instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed."
